## Key Takeaways

```
1. Every Java program = 1 JVM process + 6 default threads minimum

2. JVM threads  → work for JVM (GC, memory, signals)
   YOUR threads → work for YOUR program

3. Single core  → Concurrency  (context switching)
   Multi core   → Parallelism  (truly simultaneous)

4. Shared Heap = power + danger
   Power  → threads communicate via shared objects
   Danger → race conditions, visibility issues

5. Use synchronized for correctness
   Use volatile for visibility
   Use thread pools for performance
```

